<h1>
<span style=3D"background-color: #00FFFF">A 1.8 to 54MHz High Power Combine=
r Set</span>
<a href=3D"https://www.w6pql.com/parts_i_can_provide.htm#hfcouplers"><img b=
order=3D"0" src=3D"https://www.w6pql.com/images/kit.jpg" width=3D"125" heig=
ht=3D"50" align=3D"center"></a></h1>
<p>
<img border=3D"0" src=3D"https://www.w6pql.com/images/hf/combiner01.jpg" wi=
dth=3D"600" height=3D"642" align=3D"right">For=20
those who want to be able to combine amplifiers to get to the legal limit, =
the=20
coupler set shown here will get you there easily. When used with two of the=
=20
<a href=3D"https://www.w6pql.com/1_kw_sspa_for_1_8-54_mhz.htm">1kw RF decks=
 (1.8=20
to 54 MHz)</a>, the result is an amplifier that will just loaf along at 150=
0w=20
with lots of headroom.</p>
<p>The top one, shown with it's 100 ohm 500w isolation resistor (positioned=
 in=20
the cutout slot) will combine the outputs, and the smaller unit at the bott=
om=20
deals with the inputs.</p>
<p>These are "in phase" couplers, meaning the inputs are combined in phase =
with=20
one another. Each consists of a 2 to 1 coaxial hybrid combiner (or splitter=
) and a 2 to 1=20
transformer to return the combined (or split) impedance back to 50 ohms.</p=
>
<p>These measure only 2.5" by 4.5" and 1.625" by 3.625" respectively, and e=
xcept=20
for the high power isolation resistor on the output coupler, do not require=
 heat=20
sinking, as the insertion losses are very low. .094 FR4 is used for the hig=
h=20
power board substrate, and the more common .062 FR4 for the lower power boa=
rd.<br clear=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p>
<img border=3D"0" src=3D"https://www.w6pql.com/images/hf/combiner08.jpg" wi=
dth=3D"300" height=3D"298" align=3D"left">Here's=20
a close-up showing how the output coupler's isolation resistor is mounted a=
nd connected. On the=20
input coupler, a pair of 3w metal film resistors is used (power requirement=
s=20
there are small), but larger resistors can be used there if higher power le=
vels=20
(&gt;25w) need to be handled.<br clear=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p>When I was trying to figure out how to do this, I got dizzy reading abou=
t all=20
the various (and complex) methods, so for my own sanity, I decided to keep =
things as uncomplicated as possible. I=20
need to give credit to Motorola application note AN749, where on page 5, fi=
gure=20
7B, there is a description of a basic hybrid coupler. The only drawback was=
 the=20
2 to 1 impedance transformation, leaving one with a 25 ohm port to match ba=
ck to=20
50 ohms somehow.</p>
<p>But it turned out to be relatively easy to figure that one out; most=20
broadband transformers convert impedances by the square of the turns ratio;=
 for=20
example, a 2 to 1 turns ratio will yield a 4 to 1 impedance transformation;=
 a 3=20
turns to 1 yields a 9 to 1 ratio, and so on.</p>
<p>OK, so for a 2 to 1 transformation, we need a turns ratio that is the=20
square root of 2 (or 1.4142). Well, it turns out that a 5 to 7 turns ratio =
will=20
yield a 1.4 transformation (close enough).</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>
<img border=3D"0" src=3D"https://www.w6pql.com/images/hf/combiner09.gif" al=
ign=3D"right" width=3D"640" height=3D"463">I=20
chose 5 to 7 because it gave me the ratio I needed with the fewest number o=
f=20
turns; too many turns, and bandwidth gets limited...and we needed to get 16=
0m=20
and 6m in there. An autotransformer was the choice for this, and this schem=
atic=20
shows the basic method. I used coax for the first 2 turns because of the ti=
ght=20
coupling and lower losses.<br clear=3D"all">
<img border=3D"0" src=3D"https://www.w6pql.com/images/hf/combiner10.gif" al=
ign=3D"right" width=3D"640" height=3D"294"></p>
<p>Here's the complete schematic for the coupler. A small amount of capacit=
ance=20
(C1) is used to compensate for stray reactance, and is most effective at th=
e top=20
end (6m).</p>
<p>R1 provides the isolation between port 1 and port 2, and must have a pow=
er=20
rating at least =BC the total power at the common port. C1 should be a high=
=20
current mica type, 22pf and a 1kv rating for up to 2kw as an output combine=
r,=20
30pf and a 300v rating for up to 200w as an input divider. A small SMT 1206=
 size=20
ceramic chip capacitor can be used in place of the 30pf mica if driving a p=
air=20
of the <a href=3D"https://www.w6pql.com/1_kw_sspa_for_1_8-54_mhz.htm">HF KW=
 amps described here</a>, as=20
the most input power required in this case is less than 5w.<br clear=3D"all=
">
&nbsp;</p>
<p>Performance measurements are shown below:</p>
<p>
<img border=3D"0" src=3D"https://www.w6pql.com/images/hf/combiner02.jpg" wi=
dth=3D"640" height=3D"363" align=3D"right"></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>There isn't much lost in the output coupler, only about a tenth of a db =
at=20
the high end, and the coupling tracks closely.<br clear=3D"all">
<img border=3D"0" src=3D"https://www.w6pql.com/images/hf/combiner03.jpg" wi=
dth=3D"640" height=3D"362" align=3D"right"></p>
<p>And here's the input coupler; this one loses about 2 tenths due to the=
=20
smaller cores used in it's transformers, but it's still next to nothing, an=
d on the input side this is hardly a=20
concern (we usually have to throw away some drive power anyway).<br clear=
=3D"all">
<img border=3D"0" src=3D"https://www.w6pql.com/images/hf/combiner04.jpg" wi=
dth=3D"640" height=3D"363" align=3D"right"></p>
<p>Back to the output coupler, here's the isolation; should one of the comb=
ined=20
amps ever fail, the remaining one is well protected.<br clear=3D"all">
<img border=3D"0" src=3D"https://www.w6pql.com/images/hf/combiner05.jpg" wi=
dth=3D"640" height=3D"363" align=3D"right"></p>
<p>Plenty of isolation on the input coupler also...<br clear=3D"all">
<img border=3D"0" src=3D"https://www.w6pql.com/images/hf/combiner06.jpg" wi=
dth=3D"640" height=3D"363" align=3D"right"></p>
<p>And here's the output coupler return loss on all 3 ports, less than 1.1 =
to 1=20
VSWR from 1.8 to 54 MHz. SSPA's do like a good match, and we have it here.<=
br clear=3D"all">
<img border=3D"0" src=3D"https://www.w6pql.com/images/hf/combiner07.jpg" wi=
dth=3D"640" height=3D"363" align=3D"right"></p>
<p>And the same goes for the input coupler...<br clear=3D"all">
One final note...after using the couplers for some time, I noticed the T2 c=
ore=20
on the output transformer ran hot on 75m, and very hot on 160m. The solutio=
n was=20
to "double up" to a binocular core for T2 (only on the output coupler) as s=
hown=20
below.</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"https://www.w6pql.com/images/hf/t2binocular.jpg=
" width=3D"600" height=3D"358"></p>

